<v Speaker 1>For example, what is to wait?

00:00:23.000 --> 00:00:23.960
<v Speaker 1>Esperar.

00:00:23.960 --> 00:00:27.480
<v Speaker 1>And what is you wait informally?

00:00:27.480 --> 00:00:28.520
<v Speaker 1>Esperas.

00:00:28.520 --> 00:00:29.480
<v Speaker 1>Esperas.

00:00:29.480 --> 00:00:31.080
<v Speaker 1>And wait the order

00:00:32.420 --> 00:00:33.140
<v Speaker 1>Espera.

00:00:33.300 --> 00:00:33.940
<v Speaker 1>Espera.

00:00:33.940 --> 00:00:35.380
<v Speaker 1>That's our shortcut.

00:00:35.380 --> 00:00:38.180
<v Speaker 1>How would you say let's wait?

00:00:39.460 --> 00:00:40.660
<v Speaker 2>Esperemos.

00:00:40.660 --> 00:00:41.940
<v Speaker 1>Esperemos.

00:00:41.840 --> 00:00:42.480
<v Speaker 1>Good.

00:00:42.480 --> 00:00:44.800
<v Speaker 1>And you can also say esperamos.

00:00:44.800 --> 00:00:46.800
<v Speaker 1>It just sounds less like an order.

00:00:46.800 --> 00:00:48.800
<v Speaker 1>It would sound more like shall we wait?

00:00:48.800 --> 00:00:50.000
<v Speaker 1>Esperamos.

00:00:50.000 --> 00:00:50.960
<v Speaker 1>Shall we wait?

00:00:50.960 --> 00:00:53.680
<v Speaker 1>But then the order, Esperemos.

00:00:53.680 --> 00:00:55.519
<v Speaker 1>Let's not wait.

00:00:56.559 --> 00:00:58.000
<v Speaker 2>No esperemos.

00:00:58.000 --> 00:00:59.440
<v Speaker 1>No esperemos.

00:00:59.440 --> 00:01:00.000
<v Speaker 1>Good.

00:01:00.000 --> 00:01:06.240
<v Speaker 1>So the orders we are using with you, the different versions of you, and with we.

00:01:06.220 --> 00:01:13.980
<v Speaker 1>But maybe I want to say what I want him to do or what I want her to do or what I want them

00:01:14.439 --> 00:01:15.079
